<subSubSection id="F7D86578FFB51B02FE84FB2405A043B0" pageId="11" pageNumber="161" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="BF7D36F3FFB51B02FE84FB2405A043B0" blockId="11.[285,1680,742,1414]" pageId="11" pageNumber="161">
This is a small black ladybeetle with two reddish spots on the elytra. It occurs also in Hawaii where it was introduced from the 
<collectingCountry id="C7D57663FFB51B02FAB9FB71012C42DA" box="[1379,1578,1220,1260]" name="Philippines" pageId="11" pageNumber="161">Philippines</collectingCountry>
. We found it in many places, and apparently it was responsible for the scarcity of the mealybug 
<emphasis id="8DB6EAE1FFB51B02FDFBFA9F04404365" box="[545,838,1322,1363]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="161">
<taxonomicName id="78C24D70FFB51B02FDFBFA9F04394365" baseAuthorityName="Cockerell" baseAuthorityYear="1893" box="[545,831,1322,1363]" class="Insecta" family="Pseudococcidae" genus="Ferrisia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="161" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="virgata">Ferrisia virgata</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
as it was found associated with it as well as with other mealybugs.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
